 Abstract 
 An econometric procedure for guessing Arrow-Pratt coefficients of risk disgust is received/made from. The model of farmers giving-out land 
 among different crops, and time between fun and labor, allows for testing Arrow's guesses of decreasing total risk disgust and 
 increasing relative risk disgust. The scientific results support these guesses. Â© 1997 Elsevier Science B.V. 
 
 1. Introduction 
 
 The important works of Arrow (1971) and Pratt 
 (1964) established that under the expected-utility 
 guess there exist one-to-one relationships between preferences over random income or wealth 
 and the measures of risk disgust. Since then, the 
 different measures of risk disgust have played a 
 central role in deciding/figuring out (serving to compare two or more things) static results 
 of behavior under doubt (i.e., Sandmo, 1971; 
 Just and Zilberman, 1983). Especially, specific 
 ideas (you think are true) (related to/looking at/thinking about) the signs, high levels, and 
 behaviors with respect to wealth changes of the 
 measures are needed/demanded. Commonly, possible studies assume positive measures of risk disgust and 
 adopt Arrow's guesses on the effect of wealth on 
 the measures of risk disgust (in other words), decreasing total and increasing relative risk disgust. 
 While there exists some evidence on the 
 signs and high levels of these measures there is a 
 little evidence on the effect of wealth 
 
 * Corresponding author. 
 
 changes on them. So, the goal of this study is 
 two-fold: (i) guessing the (many, many times more/much, much less)s of 
 the measures of risk disgust; (ii) guessing the 
 effects of wealth changes on the measures, by that/in that way 
 testing Arrow's guesses about their behavior with 
 respect to income or wealth. It is worthwhile to note 
 that such scientific results are of special importance 
 to the farming-based part/area. Farming-based production is 
 seen as (large/relatively large) risk and significant 
 governmental helping action and so group measures of risk disgust and their properties with respect to wealth have very important policy effects/results/suggestions. 
 The Â·literature has tried to provide scientific 
 (event(s) or object(s) that prove something) of people' risk attitudes. These attempts may be classified into two main approaches: 
 experimental and econometric. A critical difference 
 between them is that the former is based on tests in which people are presented with possible lists of questions (related to/looking at/thinking about) risky other choices, 
 with or without real payments, while the last thing just mentioned has 
 the advantage of being based on people' actual 
 decisions. The experimental approach, for example, 
 has been used by Dillon and Scandizzo (1978) to 
 
 0169-5150/97/$17.00 Â© 1997 Elsevier Science B.V. All rights reserved. 
 PI/ S0169-5150(97)00021-2 
 
 212 
 
 Z. Bar-Shira et al.j Farming-based Money flow 17 (1997) 211-222 
 
 bring out risk attitudes of survival/income farmers in northeast Brazil, and by Binswanger (1980), Binswanger 
 (1981) and Quizon et al. (1984) to carefully study a fairly 
 large-scale experiment, with real significant payments, in (away from cities) India. 
 The econometric approach has been used in variety of facts or conditions (that surround someone). Moscardi and de Janvry (1977), 
 and Shahabuddin et al. (1986) used such an approach 
 in which the decision-makers were assumed to follow a safety-first rule. Antle (1987, 1989), Poetsley 
 and Harris (1987), Love and Buccola (1991), Pope 
 and Just (1991), and Saha et al. (1994) used econometric approaches to study of risk attitudes of decision-makers assuming expected utility (biggest increase/best possible extent). 
 Newbery and Stiglitz (1981), Robison (1982), Pope 
 (1982), Hazell (1982) and Binswanger (1982) present a complete discussion of the (connected/related) books. 
 The papers by Pope and Just, Poetsley and Harris, and Saba are the closest to this one. Pope and 
 Just developed tests for telling the difference between constant total, relative, and partial risk disgust. In 
 contrast, they did not think about/believe an ability to stretch of risk 
 disgust and so did not guess a planned way 
 in which risk disgust differs among people. 
 Hence, the clearly stated/particular guesses of Pope and Just are 
 special cases of the general model of this paper. In 
 Section 6 we compare our results to others including 
 Poetsley and Harris, and Saba. 
 A large body of (event(s) or object(s) that prove something) against the expected 
 utility guess has been piling up over past 
 20 years (i.e., Kahneman and Tversky, 1979; 
 Machina, 1987), raising some doubts as to the importance of the (before that/before now) talked about/said measures. Most of 
 the violations of the expected utility guess, 
 however, have been received with carefully planned 
 experiments. So, it is unclear whether such violations should prohibit the use of the expected utility 
 guess when studying real-world decisions. (not very long ago), Bar-Shira (1992) could find no violations of 
 the expected utility guess in production decisions of Israeli farmers. Rubinstein (1988) points to/shows 
 that the expected utility guess is likely to be 
 violated when other choices are almost the same  in the sense 
 that either prizes or chances are unable to be separated among the other choices. Buschena and Zilberman (1992) showed that the expected utility guess is less likely to hold when comparing other choice 
 
 pairs that are highly different in both importance 
 and chance. 1 However, real-life other choices appear to be (compared to other things) almost the same, but able to be separated. 
 This way the expected utility guess is (based on what's seen or what seems obvious) 
 valid for the purpose of this paper. 
 This paper go aheads as follows. Section 1 reviews 
 the (connected/related) books. Section 2 discusses the relationships between the total, relative and partial 
 measures of risk disgust, and possible responses 
 to changes in income or wealth under each. Section 3 
 outlines the model and gets some ends/end results on 
 the effect of risk on production. Section 4 gives 
 scientific background and describes the data. In Section 5, the guess procedure is organized and listed. Section 
 6 presents the results and compares them to results 
 which have been received in other studies. Then 
 ends/end results are presented. 
 
 2. Measures of risk disgust: properties and relationships 
 Arrow and Pratt first introduced the measure of 
 total risk disgust 
 (1) 
 A(W) 
