 where W points to/shows total wealth and U" and U' 
 point to/show the second and first derivatives of the von 
 Neumann-Morgenstern utility function, (match up each pair of items in order). 
 The measure of total risk disgust is appropriate 
 to describe situations in which total wealth has a 
 fixed (random/including random data points) part-income, and a (number or thing that changes) nonstochastic part-initial wealth. Arrow pointed out 
 that gut feeling hints that an person's desire 
 to begin/try a certain risky project is greater when 
 hejshe is richer. In other words, richer people should have more risky valuable things 
 in their (mix of stocks, bonds, etc./document collection). So, the measure of total risk 
 disgust should decrease with wealth. 
 As it wasations where both the (random/including random data points) and nonstochastic parts/pieces of the wealth are changing 
 (fair in amount, related to something else/properly sized compared to something else)ly, the appropriate measure IS relative 
 risk disgust, 
 (2) 
 R(W)= -(U"(W)jU'(W))W. 
 Arrow's guess is that when both initial wealth 
 and the risky project are increased by the same 
 
