 proportion, the person's desire to begin/try 
 the risky project is smaller. In other words, richer 
 people should hold a smaller proportion of risky 
 valuable things in their (mix of stocks, bonds, etc./document collection). The (intelligent/obvious) guess of 
 increasing relative risk disgust is also supported 
 mathematically. Assuming bounded utility 
 functions, 2 Arrow showed that the measure of relative risk disgust must be greater than togetherness for 
 randomly large wealth, and less than togetherness for randomly small wealth. 3 So, a continuous boring voice 
 measure of relative risk disgust must be increasing 
 with wealth and must be equal to one for some 
 wealth between zero and infinity. 
