 total risk disgust and increasing relative risk 
 disgust. Note, that E,r' = -1 is equal to R' = 
 A' W +A = 0, or in words, constant relative risk 
 disgust. The analysis in this section shows that the 
 ability to stretch of the measure of total risk disgust 
 with respect to wealth decides/figures out the behavior of all 
 three measures of risk disgust. 
 
 3. Way(s) of doing things 
 The model presented below describes the following farming situation on an Israeli Moshav: I small 
 farm owners, who form a village, set apart a fixed 
 amounts of land L among farming-based activities, 
 each &#126;aving net return 7Tj; and a fixed amount of 
 time T among fun T 1 and farm work. The technology is assumed to show constant returns to scale 
 
 Z. Bar-Shira et al.j Farming-based Money flow 17 (1997) 211-222 
 
 214 
 
 with fixed proportions production. The constant-returns-to-scale idea (you think is true) is thought of as (compared to other things) 
 harmless for this paper because the total 
 farm scale is constant in the sample relating to/connected to 
 both time and land. It follows that increasing one 
 activity must be with a decrease in another activity, leading to (giving out things in a different way) of all inputs, 
 including managerial input. So, the increase in size 
 of some activities can be (accomplished or gained) without the loss 
 of (wasting very little while working or producing something) usually caused by increasing all inputs 
 except the managerial input. The technology idea (you think is true) is further gave a reason for by Just et al. (1990). 
 What's more, labor is also a rare/not enough  input because 
 hired labor is not available and all labor input to the 
 farm has to be supplied by the owner and his family. 
 In this study the (not being there; not being present) of a labor market is due to 
 the fact that farmers exactly follow the way of thinking/basic truth/rule of self-employment. 4 The (not being there; not being present) of a labor market focuses on the importance of time portion between 
 fun and farming-based activities in the decision process. 
 Farmers get utility from both money-based wealth 
 and fun, so that their unemotional function is a 
 two-argument utility function. By choosing different 
 land portions, the farmers are choosing different 
 lotteries. In this sense the farmer's problem is the 
 same as the (person or business who gives money to help start a business)'s problem, the last thing just mentioned having to 
 decide on an valuable thing (mix of stocks, bonds, etc./document collection). Each farmer is assumed 
 to act as an expected utility (make as big as possible)r, and his 
 decision problem can be written as 
