 Future (money made/good thing received) expectations in an (surrounding conditions) 
 which is Markovian up to white noise tend to be 
 (able to change and get better) in nature (see Just, 1977). 8 So, farmer's 
 expectations can be guessed by a weighted average 
 of actual (money made/good thing received) (or its (statement about the future) when the actual 
 value is missing) over past years, where the coefficients sum to one and decline at a geometric rate (for 
 more on the bestity of this procedure see Just, 
 1977). Following Berhman (1968), the actual guess was based on only the past 3 years' (money made/good thing received), 
 because most of the explanatory power is in the 
 (money made/good thing received) of the last few years, and because of not enough data. Adapting Just (1974), the guessed expected (money made/good thing received) for farmer i at time t is 
