 The endogenous (number or thing that changes) L appears on both sides 
 of Eq. (21), suggesting a (happening at the same time) problem. To 
 resolve it, we used a two-stage instrumental changeable 
 approach. The (tools or objects used to do work or measure something) were the first and second 
 moments of the profit distribution function, (in other words), the 
 means and the parts/pieces of the variance matrix 
 (20 (numbers that change/things that change)). Because there is no part of the 
 variance matrix on the right-hand side of Eq. (21), 
 the equation is identified. 
 The first stage involves an instrumental logit 
 model. That is, 
 
