 Table 2 gives the moving backward results of Eq. (21). 
 The first and most important finding is that the 
 ability to stretch of the measure of total risk disgust is 
 -0.316. The connected T-ratio shows that it is 
 very different from zero as well as from 1. 
 This way we accept the guesses of decreasing total risk disgust and increasing relative risk disgust over the simple other choice of constant total 
 risk disgust or constant relative risk disgust. The 
 received/made from behavior of the measure of partial risk disgust is plain/honest/easy: it increases with income and 
 decreases with wealth. The results reported in Table 
 2 were gotten for r = 0.04 which was the real 
 interest rate during the watched/followed time, and by assigning the not important natural tendency to save, b, a value of 
 0.2. This value was proven true by the moshav leaders 
 as being realistic. What's more, we (did/done/completed) a sensitivity analysis to (check for truth/prove true) how strong the results were 
 to changes in the not important natural tendency to save. Table 
 3 shows the guessed values of ln a and f3 for 
 different values of b. For b = 0.10 the guessed 
 values for Ina and f3 were -10.51 and -0.37, 
 (match up each pair of items in order). For b = 0.30 the guessed values for 
 ln a and f3 were - 11.62 and - 0.29, (match up each pair of items in order). 
 
