 oo 
 
 Poetsley and Harris found the measure of partial risk 
 disgust at the middle-point point to be 0.072, 0.099, and 
 0.696, for their three different zones of Australia. 
 Hence, in two of the zones, Australian farmers showed lower degrees of partial risk disgust than 
 Israeli farmers, whereas in the third zone the degree 
 of partial risk disgust was just like that of the 
 Indian farmers. Our guessed measure of relative 
 risk disgust has a middle-point value of 0.615. Peppers 
 are given out/set aside the highest labor cost, with a middle-point of 
 US$1172 followed by tomatoes with a middle-point of 
 US$929, onions with a middle-point of US$649, melons 
 with a middle-point of US$303, and eggplant with a 
 middle-point of US$236. These results are compatible 
 with reality, where peppers and tomatoes are highlabor crops, and eggplant and melons are low-labor 
 crops. 
 To confirm our results, we note that total wealth 
 is positively related to the risk-looking (for) attitude 
 (number or thing that changes) built by the Delphi panel (with a 
 relationship-related coefficient of 0.46). The main judging requirement 
 guiding the Delphi panel members in testing the 
 risk-looking (for) attribute was the farmer desire to 
 adopt new technology such as a new variety, bug-killer, (material that makes plants grow better), etc. This positive relationship means 
 that the richer the farmer, the less (not wanting to do anything dangerous) he is. 
 
